<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="520" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,593,1125,1152]" box="[151,593,1125,1152]" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,593,1125,1152]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="(Scopoli, 1763)" authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1763" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[151,593,1125,1152]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Cavariella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegopodii">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,593,1125,1152]" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,401,1125,1152]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">Cavariella aegopodii</emphasis>
(Scopoli, 1763)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1197,1655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[151,389,1197,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Cavariella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegopodii">
<emphasis box="[151,389,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">Cavariella aegopodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here reported on Wrangel Island for the first time, and indeed reported for the first time from anywhere in the Arctic. The species is heteroecious holocyclic, with an amphigonic generation on various 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[1328,1384,1233,1259]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1328,1384,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. or, in warmer climates, it can be anholocyclic on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1830" box="[707,815,1269,1295]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Apiaceae</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dunn, J. A." box="[942,1087,1268,1295]" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" pagination="429 - 438" refId="ref9258" refString="Dunn, J. A. (1965) Studies on the aphid, Cavariella aegopodii Scop. I. On willow and carrot. Annals of Applied Biology, 56 (3), 429 - 438. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7348.1965. tb 01261. x" type="journal article" year="1965">Dunn (1965)</bibRefCitation>
showed that alatae of this species sometimes recolonize willow, so populations can persist on that host in July and August. Probably due to the short warm summer period on Wrangel Island, this species shifts to a monoecious life cycle on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[1226,1282,1341,1367]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1226,1282,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, reducing the life cycle to three generations. Finding 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[588,733,1377,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Cavariella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="9" pageNumber="520" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegopodii">
<emphasis box="[588,733,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="520">C. aegopodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the center of the island and in habitats with their food plants (thickets of shrubs in the floodplain, more characteristic of the landscapes in the southern tundra, Fig. 14), suggests that this species existed here before climate changes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
